The two attack families differ fundamentally in their visibility. \textbf{Actuator Pollution (AP)} attacks target I/O points — the setpoints, process variables, and control variables that flow through standard SCADA channels — and therefore leave measurable residuals in PV predictions. \textbf{Actuator Emulation (AE)} attacks instead corrupt internal DCS algorithm blocks (e.g., calibration scaling functions, initialisation registers, and monitor thresholds) that are invisible in standard historian logs. These attacks operate entirely within the DCS control logic layer, meaning the physical actuators behave differently from what the process engineer intended while all observable I/O signals remain within individually plausible ranges. This inherent stealth is why AE attacks are the hardest to detect and motivates the inclusion of the HAIEnd+ dataset, which exposes the internal function block outputs that AE attacks manipulate.

