Less than 1\% of samples contained missing values due to sensor errors or logging interruptions. Linear interpolation was applied to reconstruct these gaps, producing a continuous signal. Next, a \texttt{StandardScaler} is fitted exclusively on normal-only samples from the training portion, ensuring that the normalization statistics reflect legitimate plant behavior and are not distorted by attack dynamics. Columns with variance below $10^{-8}$ are automatically removed to prevent numerical instability before normalization. Sliding windows of 300 timesteps (5 minutes) input and 180 timesteps (3 minutes) target are then extracted with a stride of 60 seconds. A stride of 60 seconds was chosen to ensure that any attack event will happen in one window instead of being split. The input window of 300 s was selected to span approximately eleven times the longest causal lag identified in the process graph (26 s for \texttt{P1\_TIT03} $\leftarrow$ \texttt{P1\_PP04D}), ensuring the model observes sufficient process history to capture the slowest plant dynamics. The prediction horizon of 180 s was chosen to cover the mean attack duration observed in the HAI 23.05 dataset (213--221 s across test segments), ensuring the model's output window captures the bulk of a typical attack's effect on process variables.

The input feature space is defined by a physics-informed decomposition of the HAI testbed into its constituent control loops and physical plant (Homaei et al., 2026), without any manual feature engineering. Plant inputs consist of all sensor channels after removing the five PVs. Controller inputs are limited to the setpoint (SP), process variable (PV), and control variable (CV) for each respective loop, re-normalised using a per-loop \texttt{StandardScaler} fitted only on normal training samples to prevent attack dynamics from distorting the normalisation statistics.

\subsection{Model Design \& Selection}

\subsubsection{Overview}
\label{sec:overview}
The digital twin must predict future process variable (PV) values across a multi-loop industrial control system, under both normal operation and active attack scenarios. This requires a model that can capture sequential temporal dependencies, handle multiple interacting control loops, and generalise across operating conditions with fundamentally different dynamics.

A data-driven sequence modelling approach was adopted over physics-based alternatives for two reasons: the HAI boiler system involves complex nonlinear interactions between pressure, flow, level, and temperature that are difficult to model analytically; and the availability of labelled historical data with attack scenarios makes supervised learning the most direct path to scenario-aware prediction.

Among sequence model families — LSTM, GRU, and Transformer — GRU was selected following architectural analysis. LSTM's explicit cell state adds parameter overhead without meaningful gain at the timescales of this system. The Transformer architecture struggles with the long autoregressive rollout required at inference, accumulating error over the prediction horizon. GRU provides the best trade-off between temporal memory, parameter efficiency, and stable autoregressive rollout.

The system was modelled as a closed loop: separate GRU controller models predict actuator outputs (CVs) per control loop, which feed into a shared GRU plant model that predicts all sensor outputs (PVs). This mirrors the actual DCS structure — controllers and plant are distinct functional blocks — and allows each component to be trained and evaluated independently before closed-loop composition. The overview architecture is shown in Figure 5.
A simple GRU baseline was trained before reaching this final architecture. There was no causal structure or scenario awareness, resulting in a mean NRMSE of 1.137\% on the test set. Optuna's CMA-ES (Covariance Matrix Adaptation Evolution Strategy) was used to select the optimal hyperparameters. Over 30 trials, each hyperparameter ran for 40 epochs, and some trials were cut back at this early stage. The search covered hidden sizes of {128, 256, 512}, GRU layers of {2, 3}, dropout between 0.05 to 0.30, learning rate of 1×10⁻⁴ to 1×10⁻², batch size of {64, 128, 256}, and scheduled sampling schedule. The optimal configuration found was of 512 hidden units, 2 layers, and a 0.054 dropout, which was used for all training afterwards.

