All controllers satisfy the 10\% NRMSE gate threshold, confirming that each loop is individually well-modelled before being composed into the closed-loop plant. The two training stages then proceed as follows.

\textbf{Stage 1 — Causal plant training with uniform attack weighting.}
The plant model is initialised from the baseline checkpoint obtained during hyperparameter search, avoiding random initialisation and providing a warm start that already captures normal process dynamics. All attack windows are penalised uniformly at $3\times$ the normal window loss weight. This stage teaches the plant to distinguish attack dynamics from normal operation without yet differentiating between attack types.

\textbf{Stage 2 — Per-scenario fine-tuning.}
The best Stage 1 checkpoint is loaded and fine-tuned with per-scenario loss weights (Table~\ref{tab:scenario_weights}) calibrated to each attack type's frequency and reconstruction difficulty. This stage refines the model's sensitivity to each specific attack regime. Controllers are trained alongside the plant in both stages but their weights are fixed during Stage 2, preserving the loop-level accuracy established in pre-training.

\subsubsection{Loss Functions}

To bridge the training/inference gap introduced by teacher forcing, scheduled sampling (Bengio et al., 2015) is applied to the plant decoder. The mixing ratio $\alpha$ ramps linearly from 0 to a maximum of 0.483 over the scheduled epochs; at each decoding step, with probability $\alpha$ the model's own previous prediction is used as the next input instead of the ground truth:

\begin{equation}
  \tilde{\mathbf{y}}_{t-1} =
  \begin{cases}
    \hat{\mathbf{y}}_{t-1} & \text{with probability } \alpha \\
    \mathbf{y}_{t-1}       & \text{with probability } 1 - \alpha
  \end{cases}
\end{equation}

\paragraph{Stage 1 Loss.}
A uniform attack penalty is applied: all attack windows (scenario $> 0$) are weighted $3\times$ relative to normal windows. The temperature sensor \texttt{P1\_TIT03} receives an additional $2\times$ channel weight, yielding an effective $6\times$ penalty on its attack-window errors. The weighted loss for a batch of $B$ windows is:

\begin{equation}
  \mathcal{L}_{\text{plant}} =
  \frac{1}{B}\sum_{b=1}^{B} w_b
  \!\left[
    \frac{1}{T}\sum_{t=1}^{T}
    \left(
      \bigl\|\hat{\mathbf{y}}_{b,t}^{[{:}4]} - \mathbf{y}_{b,t}^{[{:}4]}\bigr\|^2
      + 2\,\bigl\|\hat{y}_{b,t}^{[4]} - y_{b,t}^{[4]}\bigr\|^2
    \right)
  \right]
  \label{eq:stage1_loss}
\end{equation}

where $w_b = 3$ if window $b$ contains an attack, and $w_b = 1$ otherwise.

\paragraph{Stage 2 Loss.}
The uniform attack penalty of Stage 1 is replaced with \emph{per-scenario} loss weights calibrated to the data imbalance and reconstruction difficulty of each attack type:

\begin{equation}
  \mathcal{L}_{\text{plant}} =
  \frac{1}{B}\sum_{b=1}^{B} w_{s_b}
  \!\left[
    \frac{1}{T}\sum_{t=1}^{T}
    \left(
      \bigl\|\hat{\mathbf{y}}_{b,t}^{[{:}4]} - \mathbf{y}_{b,t}^{[{:}4]}\bigr\|^2
      + 2\,\bigl\|\hat{y}_{b,t}^{[4]} - y_{b,t}^{[4]}\bigr\|^2
    \right)
  \right]
  \label{eq:stage2_loss}
\end{equation}

where $w_{s_b}$ is the scenario weight for window $b$, defined in Table~\ref{tab:scenario_weights}.

