\subsubsection{Attack Classification Using Synthetic Data}

The residual-based detector described in the previous section provides a binary indication of whether an anomaly is present, but does not identify the type of attack. Its sensitivity is also uneven: while \textit{AP\_with} is reliably detected, \textit{AP\_no} and \textit{AE\_no} remain largely undetected at practical operating thresholds.

A natural extension is to introduce a multi-class classifier (Normal / AP\_no / AP\_with / AE\_no) for finer-grained identification. However, the HAI dataset is highly imbalanced, with 3,292 Normal windows compared to only 42 \textit{AP\_no}, 37 \textit{AP\_with}, and 6 \textit{AE\_no} windows. Under these conditions, a classifier trained directly on real data is prone to overfitting, effectively memorising the limited attack samples rather than learning generalisable decision boundaries.

To address this limitation, we leverage the synthetic data generation capability introduced in Section~\ref{sec:synth_quality}. The generator is used to produce 3,292 synthetic windows per class, creating a balanced training dataset. An XGBoost classifier is then trained using 30 statistical features extracted from the five PV channels, capturing both steady-state behaviour and short-term dynamics.

The classifier is evaluated on the original real test windows. This setup—training entirely on synthetic data and testing on real data—provides a direct measure of how well the generated samples support generalisation.

Three training configurations are compared:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Baseline (Real only):} Trained on an 80\% stratified split of the real training data and tested on the held-out 20\%. Achieves Macro F1 = \textbf{0.797}, with per-class F1 of 1.00 (Normal), 0.67 (AP\_no), 0.67 (AP\_with), and 0.86 (AE\_no). Performance is reasonable on the few real attack samples available, but the small test set (20 AP\_no, 4 AP\_with, 3 AE\_no windows) limits statistical reliability.

    \item \textbf{TRTS — Synthetic only:} Trained exclusively on synthetic data (3{,}292 windows per class) and tested on the full real held-out test set. Achieves Macro F1 = \textbf{0.283}, with per-class F1 of 0.98 (Normal), 0.08 (AP\_no), 0.07 (AP\_with), and 0.00 (AE\_no). The low attack-class F1 scores reveal that synthetic trajectories do not fully capture the statistical distribution of real attack windows, particularly for low-frequency scenarios.

    \item \textbf{Mixed — Real Normal + Synthetic attacks:} Trained on real Normal windows and synthetic attack data, tested on real. Achieves Macro F1 = \textbf{0.280}, essentially matching the TRTS result, indicating that augmenting with synthetic attacks alone does not close the distribution gap between generated and real attack trajectories.
\end{itemize}

Figure~\ref{fig:clf_bar} summarises these results.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{s3_experement/s3c_experiment_bar.png}
\caption{Four-class attack classification Macro F1 under three training configurations.}
\label{fig:clf_bar}
\end{figure}

Figure~\ref{fig:clf_cm} shows the confusion matrix for the TRTS experiment. Attack classes are largely misclassified as Normal, confirming that synthetic data alone is insufficient for reliable attack identification on real data.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{s3_experement/s3c_confusion_trts.png}
\caption{Confusion matrix for the XGBoost TRTS classifier (trained on synthetic data, tested on real data). Most attack windows are misclassified as Normal, reflecting the distribution gap between synthetic and real attack trajectories.}
\label{fig:clf_cm}
\end{figure}

\paragraph{Key Insight}
The classification results reveal a fundamental limitation of the synthetic data programme: while the digital twin generates trajectories that are visually and statistically plausible (Section~\ref{sec:synth_quality}), the generated distributions do not match real attack windows closely enough to train a generalizable attack classifier. The TRTS experiment (Macro F1 = 0.283) shows that AP\_no and AP\_with are almost never correctly identified, and AE\_no achieves zero recall on real test data.

The Baseline experiment (Macro F1 = 0.797 on an 80/20 real split) demonstrates that a correctly trained XGBoost classifier \emph{can} distinguish attack types when trained on real labelled data, but real attack windows are too scarce (98 AP\_no, 20 AP\_with, 16 AE\_no training windows) to support reliable generalisation across the full test set.

These findings indicate that the residual-based binary detector (Section~\ref{sec:detection_classification}) remains the primary anomaly signal, and that the synthetic data programme's main value lies in generating plausible attack trajectories for operator training and system simulation rather than in augmenting a downstream classifier.
