Three capabilities were evaluated on the HAI 23.05 held-out test set.

\textbf{Prediction fidelity.} The GRU-Causal digital twin achieves mean NRMSE of 0.0095 across all five PV channels under normal and attack conditions, with no exponential error growth over a 90-minute chained rollout. Fast-dynamics channels (PIT01, FT03Z) stay below 0.007; slow thermal channels (TIT03) reach 0.022. Under AP\_with — the most severe attack — LIT01 error rises to 0.136, demonstrating that the model's adherence to learned physical dynamics produces a strong residual signal precisely when the system is most disrupted.

\textbf{Anomaly detection.} The residual-based binary detector achieves AUROC = 0.903 and best F1 = 0.547. Detection is near-perfect for AP\_with, whose multi-loop combustion disturbance generates residuals an order of magnitude above the normal baseline. AP\_no and AE\_no residuals overlap with the normal distribution at any operationally acceptable threshold — a fundamental consequence of the stealth built into these attack types, not a limitation of the model.

\textbf{Attack classification.} The XGBoost classifier achieves Macro F1 = 0.797 when trained and tested on real labelled data (80/20 stratified split), confirming that the 30-dimensional residual feature space is discriminative when sufficient real examples are available. However, when trained exclusively on synthetic data (TRTS protocol), Macro F1 drops to 0.283 on the real held-out test set, with AP\_no at F1 = 0.08, AP\_with at F1 = 0.07, and AE\_no at F1 = 0.00. This reveals a distribution gap between synthetic and real attack trajectories that prevents synthetic-only training from generalising. The residual-based binary detector therefore remains the primary anomaly signal; the classifier is effective only when real attack labels are available for training.
