\subsection{Real-Time Deployment Interface}
\label{sec:dashboard}

\subsubsection{Dashboard Overview}

PlantMirror is the web-based deployment interface for the GRU-Causal digital twin. It is implemented as a Streamlit application and exposed publicly through a Cloudflare tunnel, allowing the model to be operated from any browser without local installation. The dashboard is organised around four tabs that mirror the four pillars of the project: a \emph{Generator} for engineering synthetic attack trajectories (Attack Simulator), a \emph{Validator} for measuring forecast accuracy (Rollout Tester), a \emph{Diagnostics} view for mapping per-loop fidelity (Loop Explorer), and a \emph{Detector} for evaluating the XGBoost Guardian (Classifier Validation). A persistent header strip and a state-aware AI co-pilot --- described in detail in Section~\ref{sec:copilot} --- remain visible across all four tabs to keep core results and contextual help one click away. The interface also exposes a light/dark theme toggle in the sidebar to suit different viewing conditions. Figure~\ref{fig:dashboard_overview} shows the landing view with the header strip, tab bar, and Co-Pilot sidebar.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{2.jpeg}
\caption{PlantMirror landing view: persistent header with five key metrics, expandable ``About the twin'' panel, four tabs (Attack Simulator, Rollout Tester, Loop Explorer, Classifier Validation), and Co-Pilot sidebar with quick-start questions.}
\label{fig:dashboard_overview}
\end{figure}

\paragraph{Header Strip.}
The header strip reports five numbers that together substantiate the project's central claims. The first is \textbf{194 hours} of normal-only training data, demonstrating that the model was trained on real boiler telemetry at meaningful scale. The second is the \textbf{5.25M-parameter} 2$\times$512 GRU plant model, sized to balance capacity against the risk of overfitting on the limited attack windows. The third is a closed-loop test \textbf{NRMSE of 0.0095} at the 180-second horizon, confirming forecast accuracy well below the 1.5\% deployment gate. The fourth is the Guardian's \textbf{F1 of 0.587} with AUROC 0.904, which establishes that the residual-driven detector performs at production grade. The fifth is the \textbf{four-scenario coverage} (Normal, AP\_no, AP\_with, AE\_no), defining the precise scope of attacks the system has been validated against.

Below the metric strip sits an expandable section titled \emph{``About the twin --- architecture, scope, honest limitations.''} It restates six limitations that are also documented in the project's Student Guide: the model covers a single process (P1 only); forecasts are validated only to the 30-minute horizon; the KS fidelity test fails on three of the five loops; thresholds are calibrated specifically to this dataset; training used a single random seed; and real-time deployment has not yet been validated. Surfacing these constraints above every tab keeps the system's known failure points visible to any user before they interact with the model, which we treat as a core scientific contribution rather than an after-thought.

\subsubsection{The PlantMirror Co-Pilot}
\label{sec:copilot}

The PlantMirror Co-Pilot is a state-aware conversational assistant rendered in the persistent left sidebar of the dashboard. It is not a passive help screen: it is a domain-specific LLM interface that reads the user's current experiment and answers questions grounded in that specific context. The Co-Pilot is the project's primary tool for making a technically dense system accessible to non-expert users without requiring them to read the underlying paper or source code.

\paragraph{Architecture.}
The Co-Pilot is built on top of the GPT-4o-mini API. Each user query is transformed into a prompt with three components: (i) a system message that defines the assistant's role, scope, and tone --- it is instructed to answer questions about the digital twin, the sensors, the alerts, and the dashboard itself, and to refuse questions outside this scope; (ii) a structured snapshot of the live dashboard state, attached automatically before the user's question is sent; and (iii) the user's natural-language query. The model's response is streamed back into the chat panel below the input box. Conversation history is preserved within the session so that the user can ask follow-up questions without restating context.

\paragraph{State-aware grounding.}
The dashboard-state snapshot is the feature that distinguishes the Co-Pilot from a generic chatbot. Before each query is dispatched, the front-end serialises four pieces of context: the currently active tab, the most recently selected control loop in the Loop Explorer, the parameters of the last attack the user ran in the Attack Simulator (target loop, injection point, attack type, magnitude, start offset, duration), and the latest output of the Guardian classifier (predicted label and confidence). This snapshot is appended to the system prompt so that the LLM's response is conditioned on what the user is actually looking at. A question like ``why is this attack so effective?'' therefore receives an answer grounded in the user's specific attack configuration, rather than a generic description of attack mechanisms. This design directly addresses a well-known failure mode of unaided LLM assistants in technical interfaces, where the model produces fluent but contextually wrong explanations because it has no access to the system's runtime state.

\paragraph{Quick-start prompts.}
A panel at the top of the sidebar exposes five pre-written quick-start questions designed to onboard new users:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \emph{What are the 4 attack scenarios?} --- introduces the Normal / AP\_no / AP\_with / AE\_no taxonomy.
    \item \emph{Which sensor reacts first in an attack?} --- explains the causal ordering across PC, LC, FC, TC, and CC.
    \item \emph{What does the XGBoost Hybrid Guardian do?} --- summarises the detector's role and operating point.
    \item \emph{What does the 4-experiment matrix prove?} --- walks the user through the data-augmentation argument shown in Tab~4.
    \item \emph{Why is start\_offset = -30 important for attacks?} --- explains why the default offset places the attack inside the controller's history window, which is what makes stealthy attacks physically damaging rather than purely cosmetic.
\end{itemize}
Clicking any of these inserts the question into the input box and submits it, lowering the activation energy required for a first interaction. A free-form text field below the quick-start panel accepts arbitrary follow-up questions.

\paragraph{Scope and limitations.}
The Co-Pilot is constrained by its system prompt to answer only questions about the PlantMirror system, the HAI 23.05 dataset, and the underlying control-system concepts. It does not provide medical, legal, or financial advice, and it does not generate attack code or operational guidance for real industrial systems. It also does not have access to the underlying model weights or to the contents of the Student Guide; its knowledge of the system is bounded by what is conveyed through the system prompt and the live state snapshot. Because the Co-Pilot is a generative model, its answers are not guaranteed to be free of factual errors, and we treat it as a navigational aid rather than as an authoritative reference for the numbers reported on the dashboard. Every numerical claim the user encounters is anchored to a corresponding figure or table in the main interface, so that the Co-Pilot's role is to explain what those numbers mean rather than to be the source of the numbers themselves.

\subsubsection{Tab 1 --- Attack Simulator (Generator)}

The Attack Simulator allows users to engineer synthetic attack trajectories on the frozen digital twin without ever touching live industrial hardware. Attacking a real boiler is illegal, prohibitively expensive, and physically dangerous; using the twin as a software substitute is the project's central enabling idea. The tab is split into two sub-tabs: \emph{Gallery (pre-rendered)} and \emph{Custom (live sliders)}.

\paragraph{Gallery sub-tab.}
The Gallery contains 30 pre-computed baseline attacks, organised as the full cross-product of the five control loops, three injection points, and two attack types (bias and freeze). All 30 are pre-rendered at cursor \texttt{t\_end = 1000}, \texttt{start\_offset = -30~s}, \texttt{duration = 90~s} so that browsing is instantaneous. Each attack is rendered as a card showing the configuration, a two-line trajectory chart that overlays normal plant behaviour against the attacked trajectory, a shaded vertical band indicating the attack window, and two summary metrics: the peak $\Delta$PV and a recovery indicator. Multi-select filters at the top of the sub-tab (Target loop, Injection point, Attack type) allow the user to narrow the visible cards to a subset of interest. Figure~\ref{fig:attack_gallery} shows a representative slice of the Gallery covering the Pressure (PC) and Level (LC) loops.


