Each card reports the attack configuration (loop $\cdot$ injection point $\cdot$ attack type), magnitude, peak $\Delta$PV, and recovery status. The first six cards (PC family) show small peak deviations because pressure recovers quickly; the LC family below shows much larger deviations under SP and CV attacks at magnitude~20.

\paragraph{Custom sub-tab.}
The Custom sub-tab exposes live sliders for the target loop, injection point, attack type, scenario embedding, start offset, duration, magnitude, and replay cursor. Selecting a configuration and clicking \emph{Run attack} triggers a forward pass through the GRU plant and the five controllers, returning the modified trajectory in real time. This enables interactive exploration of the attack design space far beyond the 30 pre-computed baselines. Figure~\ref{fig:attack_custom} shows the slider layout.

Three injection points are supported, each targeting a distinct location in the control loop. A \textbf{setpoint (SP)} attack alters the target value the controller is tracking, fooling the controller into driving the plant towards an incorrect operating point. A \textbf{control variable (CV)} attack tampers with the actuator command after the controller has issued it, so that the plant receives a different instruction than the one the controller intended. A \textbf{process variable (PV)} attack spoofs the sensor reading the controller observes, which deceives both the controller and the operator about the actual physical state. Two attack types govern how the injected value is constructed: \emph{bias} adds a constant offset, and \emph{freeze} holds the signal at its value at the moment of injection. The replay-cursor control supports a third regime in which a time-lagged segment of past data is substituted for the current signal. The default \texttt{start\_offset} of $-30$ seconds places the attack inside the controller's 300-second history window, which is what gives stealthy attacks their physical impact: an attack injected outside this window only changes the operator HMI view without poisoning the controller's internal state.

\subsubsection{Tab 2 --- Rollout Tester (Validator)}

The Rollout Tester quantifies the model's predictive accuracy across both the training horizon and the longer extrapolation window. A radio selector at the top switches between two evaluation modes: \emph{3 min (180 s) --- training horizon}, which reports the closed-loop forecast produced by the main GRU plant, and \emph{30 min (1800 s) --- long-horizon plant (v2)}, which reports the open-loop forecast generated by a fine-tuned variant of the model that builds on the 3-minute checkpoint through curriculum learning. The 30-minute mode is open-loop in the sense that it consumes the actual recorded control inputs from the dataset rather than predictions from the controller twins, which isolates plant forecast accuracy from any controller-side error accumulation.

A second selector lets the user filter the displayed NRMSE by scenario --- Overall (all scenarios mixed), Normal, AP\_no, AP\_with, or AE\_no --- so that the user can directly compare the model's accuracy under benign and adversarial conditions. Figure~\ref{fig:rollout_tester} shows the per-PV NRMSE bar chart and the corresponding pass/fail pills under the Overall scenario.

