The table makes the model's honest limitations explicit. The pressure (PC) and flow (FC) loops pass the KS fidelity test with values of 0.060 and 0.067 respectively, indicating that synthetic and real distributions are statistically close. The temperature (TC), coolant (CC), and level (LC) loops warn or fail, with KS values of 0.157, 0.121, and 0.215. These three loops are dominated by slow physical dynamics --- thermal inertia in TC and CC, integrating fluid behaviour in LC --- and the model's residual mismatch on these channels is a real consequence of those dynamics rather than a bug in the dashboard. Surfacing the failures in the diagnostics view, rather than hiding them, is what allows the synthetic data produced by the twin to be used responsibly: downstream consumers know exactly which loops can be trusted for data augmentation and which require caution.

The CV-to-PV lag column surfaces a complementary insight. PC and FC drive their respective process variables with short lags of 7 and 5 seconds and exhibit the highest causal coupling to other loops, while CC at 26 seconds is the slowest, reflecting the heavy thermal inertia of the coolant pump. The Loop Explorer therefore maps the physical limits of the digital twin and not just its statistical accuracy, illustrating how each loop behaves in relation to the others.

\subsubsection{Tab 4 --- Classifier Validation (Detector)}

The Classifier Validation tab presents the XGBoost Guardian and the four-experiment validation that justifies the use of synthetic data in its training set. The Guardian itself is an \texttt{XGBClassifier} with 129 trees, maximum depth 4, and learning rate 0.089, Optuna-tuned over 15 trials. It watches all 133 raw sensor columns at 1~Hz and was trained on a mixed corpus of 199{,}078 real-train rows plus 36{,}000 synthetic rows generated by the digital twin (235{,}078 rows total). XGBoost was chosen over a deep network because, on tabular data with this row count, gradient-boosted trees train roughly two orders of magnitude faster, are inherently feature-interpretable, and outperform deep models in our internal comparisons.

At the production operating threshold of 0.35, the Guardian achieves an F1 of 0.587, AUROC of 0.904, precision of 0.648, and recall of 0.536. The corresponding confusion matrix records 79{,}520 true negatives, 1{,}308 false positives, 2{,}408 true positives, and 2{,}084 false negatives, demonstrating that the residual signal is sufficient to flag attacks at a usable false-positive rate even when the underlying class distribution is severely imbalanced. We note that this F1 figure is distinct from --- and uses a different threshold than --- the simpler residual-only detector reported in Section~\ref{sec:detection_classification}, which operates at threshold 0.198 and achieves F1 = 0.547. The Guardian extends that residual detector by combining the residual signal with handcrafted statistical features through XGBoost, producing the higher F1 that appears on the header strip.

