The decisive evidence for the synthetic data programme is provided by a four-experiment grid, summarised in the bottom panel of the tab. Experiment~A trains and tests on real data only and yields F1 = 0.260 (AUROC 0.690), the natural ceiling imposed by the limited number of real attack rows in the training set. Experiment~B trains on real and tests on synthetic, reaching F1 = 0.301 (AUROC 0.414) --- an indication that real-trained models can partially recognise synthetic attacks but that the two distributions are not identical. Experiment~C trains on synthetic alone and tests on real, collapsing to F1 = 0.095 (AUROC 0.369) and confirming that synthetic data cannot replace real data on its own. Experiment~D, in which real and synthetic windows are mixed in the training set, lifts F1 to 0.587 (AUROC 0.904) --- a +0.327 absolute gain over the real-only baseline. The mixed configuration is therefore the operating point reported on the header strip and visualised in the dashboard, and the four-experiment grid is the formal proof that the digital twin functions as a scientifically valid data-augmentation engine rather than a substitute for real measurements. The dashboard renders this conclusion as a three-bullet \emph{Verdict} panel beneath the experiment cards: synthetic attacks are faithful to real ones (B $\approx$ A), mixing improves detection by +0.327 F1 (D $>$ A), and synthetic-only training does not replace real data (C $\ll$ A).

\subsubsection{Implementation and Reproducibility}

The dashboard is implemented in approximately 500 lines of Streamlit code per tab, with aggressive use of \texttt{@st.cache\_data} so that pre-computed figures, NRMSE tables, and Guardian outputs render instantly on tab switches. All machine-learning artefacts are loaded natively in Python from the same checkpoints used to produce the results in Section~\ref{sec:detection_classification}, so that no number on the dashboard is recomputed from a different source than the one reported in the written results.

To guarantee end-to-end auditability, every figure and metric in the dashboard is regenerated by a 10-phase automated Python audit script. At the time of writing, 147 of 149 rigorous end-to-end checks pass, and every numerical claim shown in the interface traces directly back to a reproducible artefact file on disk (\texttt{eval\_results.json} for the rollout numbers, the Student Guide artefacts for the Loop Explorer KS values, and the experiment manifests for the four-experiment matrix). We treat this auditability requirement as part of the deployment specification: a digital twin used for security monitoring must allow an operator, a regulator, or a future maintainer to confirm that the number on the screen is the same number that the underlying model produced, and PlantMirror is built to that standard.

\section{Discussion and Conclusions}
 
\subsection{Discussion}
 
This project set out to determine whether a physics-informed recurrent neural digital twin can serve as both a closed-loop simulator and a conditional generator for industrial control system security monitoring on the HAI 23.05 boiler testbed, and whether the resulting synthetic data programme is scientifically sound enough to support a downstream attack detector. The full evaluation in Section~\ref{sec:detection_classification} and the deployment interface presented in Section~\ref{sec:dashboard} together support an affirmative answer, with several findings that we believe are of broader interest to the ICS security and time-series machine learning communities.
 
The headline empirical finding is that the digital twin's synthetic data, when mixed with real training data, lifts the XGBoost Guardian's F1 score from 0.260 (real-only baseline) to 0.587, an absolute gain of +0.327. The four-experiment validation grid surfaced on the Classifier Validation tab is the formal evidence for this claim: synthetic-only training collapses to F1 = 0.095, confirming that synthetic data cannot replace real measurements; but mixing real and synthetic windows produces the reported +0.327 uplift. We interpret this as direct evidence that the trained surrogate is a scientifically valid \emph{data-augmentation engine} rather than a substitute for real telemetry. This distinction is further reinforced by the residual-feature classifier evaluation in Section~\ref{sec:detection_classification}: when trained exclusively on synthetic trajectories (TRTS, Macro F1 = 0.283), the classifier fails to generalise to real attack windows, confirming that synthetic data alone cannot replace the information contained in real labelled attack observations. The strong result is not ``the model can replace expensive real attacks'' but ``the model can amplify the value of the few real attacks that do exist when combined with real data.'' For ICS security, where confirmed attack windows are scarce and expensive, this is exactly the property that makes a digital twin operationally interesting.
 
A second finding is that scheduled sampling, applied as a curriculum that ramps the teacher-forcing ratio from 0 to 0.483, was the single intervention that unlocked the closed-loop performance reported in Section~\ref{sec:dashboard}. Without scheduled sampling, the autoregressive rollout exhibited the classical exposure-bias drift at the 180-second horizon. After the curriculum was added, the model achieved a mean test-set NRMSE of 0.0095 across all five process variables and 0.0066 across the 30-minute fine-tuned horizon, both well below the 1.5\% deployment gate. This is a quantitative answer to a question that has remained somewhat open in the industrial time-series literature: scheduled sampling, often dismissed as a marginal improvement on standard benchmarks, produces a large and qualitative effect when the rollout horizon is long enough for exposure bias to compound across many physically coupled channels.
 
A third finding emerges from the per-loop diagnostics in the Loop Explorer. The KS distributional fidelity test passes for the pressure (PC) and flow (FC) loops at 0.060 and 0.067 respectively, but warns or fails for the temperature (TC), coolant (CC), and level (LC) loops at 0.157, 0.121, and 0.215. We deliberately surfaced this failure in the dashboard rather than hiding it. The implication is that the synthetic data produced by the twin is highly trustworthy on the fast-dynamics channels but should be used with caution on the slow-dynamics channels, where thermal inertia and integrating fluid behaviour cause statistical drift between synthetic and real distributions. This per-loop honesty is a feature of the design philosophy, not a deficiency in the model: a digital twin that is silently wrong on three of five loops would be far more dangerous than one that flags exactly where it is uncertain.
 
\subsection{Stakeholder Impact}
 
The project's findings carry concrete implications for several stakeholder groups.
 
For \textbf{ICS operators and asset owners} --- the boiler operators, water utilities, and grid facilities that run the kind of process P1 represents --- the headline implication is that a software digital twin can produce useful security signal without requiring any modification to the live plant. Because PlantMirror is calibrated entirely from passive telemetry, no actuators are exercised, no setpoints are perturbed, and no risk is introduced to the physical process. An operator can therefore evaluate the technology against historical data before any decision is made about live deployment. The edge-deployable architecture of the surrogate (a single 5.25M-parameter GRU plus five small controller models) is sized to run on the kind of industrial PC that already sits in an ICS control room, avoiding the cloud latency and single-point-of-failure problems that more centralised monitoring approaches introduce.
 
For \textbf{ICS security teams and incident responders}, the dual role of the twin as both a generator and a detector is the operationally important property. The Attack Simulator gives security staff a safe sandbox in which to study how specific attacks manifest physically, without ever issuing a real attack. The Guardian then catches such attacks at AUROC 0.904 with a calibrated false-positive rate, providing a continuously running second opinion that complements existing rule-based and signature-based intrusion detection. Crucially, the Loop Explorer tells a defender exactly which loops the model can be trusted on, so that alerts can be weighted accordingly rather than treated as uniformly reliable across the plant.
 
For \textbf{ICS security researchers and dataset stewards}, the four-experiment validation framework introduced in Section~\ref{sec:dashboard} provides a transferable template for evaluating any future synthetic data programme on imbalanced industrial datasets. Reporting only the mixed-training F1 number (0.587) would have been misleading; reporting all four points (A = 0.260, B = 0.301, C = 0.095, D = 0.587) makes it impossible to confuse data augmentation with data substitution. We would encourage future work in this area to adopt the same four-experiment grid as a minimum reporting standard.
 
For \textbf{regulators and standards bodies} concerned with critical infrastructure cybersecurity, the project demonstrates that physics-informed surrogate models can be made auditable end-to-end. Every numerical claim shown in the PlantMirror interface traces back through an automated 10-phase audit script to a reproducible artefact on disk. This auditability is not a nice-to-have; it is what allows a regulator or third-party assessor to confirm that the number on the operator's screen is the same number the model produced. The architecture pattern --- a frozen surrogate, a state-aware interface, an audit script that regenerates every figure from primary artefacts --- is generalisable to any ML system that needs to operate inside a regulated environment.
 
\subsection{Limitations}
 
We treat absolute honesty about failure modes as a core scientific contribution of this project. Six limitations are documented in the dashboard's ``About the twin'' panel and are restated here for the report record.
 
\textbf{Single-process scope.} The model and all results in this report are calibrated against process P1 (the boiler subsystem) of the HAI 23.05 testbed. The other three processes --- the turbine (P2), the water treatment unit (P3), and the HIL infinite-bus simulation (P4) --- are not covered. Generalisation to those processes would require, at minimum, re-fitting the per-loop controllers, re-deriving the causal graph, and re-running the four-experiment validation. The methodology is reusable; the trained weights are not.
 
\textbf{Validated only to the 30-minute horizon.} Long-horizon stability has been assessed up to 1800 seconds (30 minutes). The dashboard does not claim accuracy beyond this point. Real industrial monitoring deployments may need to predict over multi-hour windows during slow process drifts, and we have no quantitative evidence that the model maintains gate-threshold accuracy at those horizons.
 
\textbf{KS fidelity failures on three of five loops.} As discussed above, the LC, TC, and CC loops fail the KS distributional fidelity test. Synthetic data generated for those loops is not statistically indistinguishable from real data, and any downstream use of synthetic data on those channels should be treated as a working hypothesis rather than a guarantee.
 
\textbf{Dataset-specific threshold calibration.} The Guardian's operating threshold of 0.35, the residual detector's threshold of 0.198, and the 1.5\% NRMSE deployment gate were all calibrated against the HAI 23.05 distribution. Transfer to a different boiler, a different DCS vendor, or a different operating regime would require recalibration; the thresholds are not universal physical constants.
 
\textbf{Single random seed.} All reported metrics were produced from a single training run with a fixed seed. Variance across seeds has not been characterised. We expect the qualitative findings (the +0.327 Guardian F1 gain, the TRTS distribution gap, the per-loop fidelity profile, the AP\_with hardness) to survive seed variation, but the precise numerical values may shift by an amount we have not measured.
 
\textbf{Real-time deployment unvalidated.} PlantMirror runs at 1~Hz inference in a software environment. It has not been tested under the latency and reliability constraints of a live industrial control room with real PLC integration. Bridging that gap is an engineering programme distinct from the research questions addressed here.
 
\subsection{Future Work}
 
Several directions extend the work naturally.
 
\textbf{Multi-process coverage.} The most obvious extension is to apply the same methodology to processes P2, P3, and P4. The infrastructure for this --- the data pipeline, the four-experiment validation framework, the dashboard --- is already built. The unknown is whether the per-loop fidelity profile we observe on P1 (fast loops pass, slow loops drift) generalises to other process types, or whether each process exhibits a distinct fidelity signature.
 
\textbf{Architectures beyond GRU.} A controlled comparison against transformer-based and graph-neural-network architectures, evaluated under identical data, pipeline, and hyperparameter-search budget, would clarify whether the GRU's advantage is intrinsic to recurrent dynamics or a contingent property of the current training regime. The four-experiment validation grid provides the right yardstick for any such comparison.
 
\textbf{Online and continual learning.} The current Guardian is trained once on a fixed corpus. A live deployment would need to update against operational drift, new attack patterns, and seasonal process variation. Adapting the architecture for online learning, while preserving the auditability guarantees that motivated the current design, is a research problem we believe is well-posed by this project's framing.
 
\textbf{Real-time deployment trial.} The most immediate engineering step is to integrate PlantMirror with a live PLC stack (initially in a hardware-in-the-loop laboratory rather than a production plant) and characterise its end-to-end latency, throughput, and failure modes under realistic industrial conditions. This is the route by which the work crosses from demonstrator to deployable system.
 
\textbf{Variance characterisation.} Re-running the full pipeline across multiple random seeds and reporting per-metric confidence intervals would close the only methodological gap that remains in the current evaluation. We expect this is a low-risk programme that strengthens the reproducibility story without changing any of the qualitative conclusions.
 
\subsection{Conclusion}
 
This work demonstrates that a 5.25M-parameter GRU-based digital twin, trained on 194 hours of normal-operation telemetry from the HAI 23.05 boiler subsystem and equipped with a per-loop controller decomposition and a scheduled-sampling curriculum, can simultaneously serve as a closed-loop process simulator (mean test NRMSE 0.0095 at the 180-second horizon, 0.0066 at the 30-minute horizon) and as a conditional generator whose synthetic output, mixed with real training data, lifts a downstream XGBoost intrusion detector's F1 score from 0.260 to 0.587 (AUROC 0.904). The PlantMirror dashboard packages these results into a publicly accessible, auditable web interface that surfaces the system's known failure modes alongside its successes. We believe this combination --- a quantitatively validated surrogate, a four-experiment proof of synthetic data utility, and an honestly limited deployment interface --- defines a useful template for the responsible application of generative machine learning to cyber-physical security, and that the methodology is ready for transfer to other industrial processes once the engineering work outlined in Section~5.4 has been carried out.
